    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Basic Sentence Structure",
      "explanation": "Indonesian follows a Subject-Verb-Object (SVO) word order, similar to English. The pronoun 'saya' means 'I' or 'me', and there is no verb conjugation in Indonesian -- the verb stays the same regardless of the subject. To make a simple statement, just place the subject before the verb: 'Saya mengerti' (I understand). To negate, add 'tidak' before the verb: 'Saya tidak mengerti' (I don't understand).",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "I understand.",
          "target_primary": "Saya mengerti.",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "I don't understand.",
          "target_primary": "Saya tidak mengerti.",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "I am fine.",
          "target_primary": "Saya baik.",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "I am sorry.",
          "target_primary": "Saya minta maaf.",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Time-Based Greetings in Indonesia",
      "content": "Indonesians use different greetings depending on the time of day. 'Selamat pagi' is used from dawn until about 11 AM, 'Selamat siang' covers roughly 11 AM to 3 PM, 'Selamat sore' is for 3 PM until sunset, and 'Selamat malam' is used after dark. In casual settings, especially among younger people, you'll often hear just 'Pagi!' or 'Malam!' without the 'Selamat'. The word 'Selamat' itself means 'safe' or 'blessed', so these greetings literally wish safety and blessings upon the other person. When addressing someone older or of higher status, it is polite to use 'Pak' (sir/Mr.) or 'Bu' (ma'am/Mrs.)."
    }
